Put in a container div with another div in it and in it a Hello Twittister and then a label to enter a new twittister handle and a textbox and then below it text that outputs what their new twittister handle is: 
  <div class="container">
    <div >
    	<p>Helo Twittister</p>
      <label>What do you want ur twittister handle to be?</label>
      <input type="text" />
      <h2>Your twittister handle is: </h2>
      <h2>twittister.com/ </h2>
    </div>
  </div>	

Create a variable object in your js file that is the angular module: 
	In ur js file:
	var angularApp = angular.module('angularApp', []);

Add that angular module reference as an angular directive to ur html element:
	In the html tag: 
	ng-app="angularApp"

Create a basic controller in the angular module of the js file with the name of 'handle': 
	angularApp.controller('mainController', function() {
	});

Set up some string interpolation by: 

Add the scope service to your controller: 
	Should look like this: 
	angularApp.controller('mainController', ['$scope', function ($scope ) {
  }]);

Add a new object/var in the scope called name and give it your name in string: 
	In the controller: 
	$scope.name = 'Kenny Ken ken';

Add a directive to a div in ur html to reference the controller: 
  <div ng-controller="mainController" >
    <label>What do you want ur twittister handle to be?</label>
    <input type="text" />
    <h2>Your twittister handle is: </h2>
    <h2>twittister.com/ {{handle}} </h2>
	</div>

Add some extra html using Angular string intperpolation to insert your name into something like "How are you Kenny":
  <div class="container">
    <div >
    	<p>Helo Twittister. How are you {{name}}</p>
      <label>What do you want ur twittister handle to be?</label>
      <input type="text" />
      <h2>Your twittister handle is: </h2>
      <h2>twittister.com/ </h2>
    </div>
  </div>		

Add a model directive to a text box:
	In the same div: 
	<input type="text" ng-model="handle"/>

Create a model in the controller to connect with the model in the view
	In the controller: 
	$scope.handle = '';

Add another service called $timeout and use it in the controller by passing it a function that changes the string content of the name var to something else after two seconds: 
	angularApp.controller('mainController', ['$scope', '$timeout',  function('$scope', '$timeout' ) {
		$timeout(function() {
			$scope.name = 'Willy Wonka';
		}, 2000);
  }]);	

